  <info>
    <title>Creating storage pools</title><!-- can be changed via merge
in the assembly -->
    <!-- add author's e-mail -->
    <meta name="maintainer" content="jsindelarova@suse.com" its:translate="no"/>
    <abstract><!-- can be changed via merge in the assembly -->
      <para>
       The topic covers creating virtual machines using &cockpit;.
      </para>
    </abstract>
  </info>
  
    <para>
      A storage pool is designated storage devices which a virtual machine can utilize. Pools are
      not esential to run your virtual machines.
    </para>
      <para> 
        To create a
      pool, click <guimenu>Create storage pool</guimenu>. A new popup windows opens. In the window
      specify the following details:   
      
      </para>
<variablelist>
  <varlistentry>
    <term><guilabel>Connection</guilabel></term>
    <listitem>
      <para>Specify if the pool is accessible for a regular user by selecting <guilabel>User
      session</guilabel>, or for a user with <command>sudo</command> privileges by
      selecting <guilabel>System</guilabel>.
      </para>
    </listitem>
  </varlistentry>
  <varlistentry>
    <term><guilabel>Name</guilabel></term>
    <listitem>
      <para>
        Enter the pool name.
      </para>
    </listitem>
  </varlistentry>
  <varlistentry>
    <term><guilabel>Type</guilabel></term>
    <listitem>
      <para>There you can
        create the following types of pools: <guilabel>Filesystem directory</guilabel>,
        <guilabel>Network file system</guilabel>, <guilabel>iSCSI target</guilabel>,
        <guilabel>Physical disk device</guilabel>, <guilabel>LVM volume group</guilabel>, and
        <guilabel>iSCSI direct target</guilabel>. 
        </para>
  </listitem>
  </varlistentry>
  <varlistentry>
    <term><guilabel>Start pool when host boots</guilabel></term>
    <listitem>
      <para>
If checked (default), the pool is started when the host is booted.
      </para>
    </listitem>
  </varlistentry>
  <varlistentry>
    <term>Other details</term>
    <listitem>
      <para>
        Other details are specific to each pool type and are described in the following sections.
      </para>
    </listitem>
  </varlistentry>
</variablelist>
      

      <section xml:id="cockpit-creating-virtual-machines-pools-filesystem">
        <title>File system pools</title>
        <para>
          The <guilabel>Filesystem directory</guilabel> pool is created in a local directory.
          Besides the common details, select the <guilabel>Target path</guilabel>. That is a
          directory on the host file system.
        </para>        
      </section>

      <section xml:id="cockpit-creating-virtual-machines-pools-nfs">
        <title>Network file system</title>
        <para>
          The pool is created on an NFS server. Besides the common details, fill in also the
          following ones:
        </para>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term><guilabel>Target path</guilabel></term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
The path on the host machine where the pool is mounted.
              </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term><guilabel>Host</guilabel></term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
Host name of the NFS server.
              </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term><guilabel>Source path</guilabel></term>
            <listitem>
              <para>The path on a NFS server that is used to store the pool.</para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
      </section>
      
      <section xml:id="cockpit-creating-virtual-machines-pools-iscsi">
        <title>iSCSI target</title>
        <para>
          The pool is created on a iSCSI target. Besides the common options, enter the following items:
        </para>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term><guilabel>Target path</guilabel></term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
The path on the host machine where the pool is mounted.
              </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term><guilabel>Host</guilabel></term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
Host name of the iSCSI target.
              </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term><guilabel>Source path</guilabel></term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                Enter the target IQN. The format is
                <literal>iqn.yyyy-mm.naming-authority:unique-name</literal>.
               </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
      </section>

      <section xml:id="cockpit-creating-virtual-machines-pools-physical">
        <title>Physical disk device</title>
        <para>
          The pool is on a physical disk mounted on the host. Besides the common details, fill in also the
          following ones:
        </para>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term><guilabel>Target path</guilabel></term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
The path on the host machine where the pool is mounted.
              </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>          
          <varlistentry>
            <term><guilabel>Source path</guilabel></term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
               Is the identification of the disk device, for example, <filename>/dev/sdc</filename>.
               </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term><guilabel>Format</guilabel></term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
Select the format of the disk:
              </para>
              <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>
                  <para>
                    <literal>dos</literal> for BIOS systems with MBR
                  </para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                  <para>
                    <literal>gpt</literal> for UEFI systems
                  </para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                  <para>
                    <literal>dvh</literal> provides support for SGI disk volume headers
                  </para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                  <para>
                    <literal>mac</literal> for Apple systems.
                  </para>
                </listitem>
              </itemizedlist>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
      </section>

      <section xml:id="cockpit-creating-virtual-machines-pools-lvm">
<title>LVM volume group</title>
<para>
  The pool is located in LVM. Besides the common details you need to specify the volume group,
  the pool should use.
</para>
      </section>

      <section xml:id="cockpit-creating-virtual-machines-pools-iscsi-initiator">
        <title>iSCSI direct target</title>
        <para>
          The pool is created using an iSCSI initiator. Besides the common details, fill in also the
          following ones:
        </para>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term><guilabel>Host</guilabel></term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
The iSCSI target host name
              </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term><guilabel>Source path</guilabel></term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                Enter the target IQN. The format is
                <literal>iqn.yyyy-mm.naming-authority:unique-name</literal>.
              </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term><guilabel>Iniciator</guilabel></term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                Enter the initiator IQN. The format is
                <literal>iqn.yyyy-mm.naming-authority:unique-name</literal>.
              </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
      </section>    
   
</topic>
